    <summary>Award-winning font designed specifically to help with legibility and improve readability for people with low vision</summary>
    <description>Atkinson Hyperlegible is a typeface, carefully crafted to improve legibility and readability for individuals with low vision. The font is named after Braille Institute founder, J. Robert Atkinson. What makes it different from traditional typography design is that it focuses on letterform distinction to increase character recognition, ultimately improving readability.

The Braille Institute has made this free for anyone to use, under the SIL Open Font License.

Atkinson Hyperlegible Next, a refined version of Atkinson Hyperlegible, improves on the original in every way. It features new weights, improved kerning, refined curves, added symbols, and additional language support.
Atkinson Hyperlegible Mono, a monospace version of Atkinson Hyperlegible, offers new opportunities for developers with low vision. 

* Seven weights — Light to Extrabold — in both upright and italic styles and for both Next and Mono.
* A variable font for both Next and Mono
* 370+ glyphs per font style
* Accent characters [supporting over 150 languages](https://braileinstitute.box.com/s/7iwrt350qau7dzsl19n3d9n73czz2zww)
* For designers and anyone interested in making written materials easier to read across the entire visual-ability spectrum
* Free for personal use and all commercial applications!

![Sample of Atkinson Hyperlegible Next font characters to show concepts of Recognizable Footprints and Differentiated Letterforms](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Z1idzrzJh-qUyp4LA4Yd2wLaLf6Jc0b2eS7TH37bMGCKEri0A46OAeBL3Q=w800)
![Example comparison of Monospaced font and Proportional font](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/z500LleKJx3HyvNQzzQIj3-Vx4Jfwqs9_d4gypDutXCAAWe-A0tYlQJ_AEg=w800)

## Unique design features
* **Unambiguous Letterforms** Letters have received special care to ensure they’re legible and clear.
* **Clear Uprights** Similarly-shaped upright letters are distinctly different.
* **Distinct Pairs** Matching letter pairs are clearer and easier to identify.
* **Open Counters** Large areas inside letters, called counters, keep characters clear.
* **Spurs and Tails** Angled spurs and longer tails help increase differentiation.
* **Special Circles** Circular elements reflect the heritage of the Braille Institute.

Informational sheet about the original Atkinson Hyperlegible font, with samples of informational brochures, business card, and more with text in the font: [Download Summary Document [.pdf]](https://github.com/googlefonts/atkinson-hyperlegible/blob/main/docs/BIA_AtkinsonHyerlegible-Specimen_2020-02-10.pdf)
    </description>
